We recommended and Management agreed on the following:
Instruct the Municipal Accountant and Municipal General Service Officer to facilitate the reconciliation of records through availing of the one-time cleansing of PPE  mandated by COA Circular 2020-006 dated January 31, 2020 in order to address concerns on the existence and completeness of PPE;
Instruct the Municipal Accountant, Municipal Engineer and Municipal General Services Officer to facilitate the establishment of a policy and set of procedures in the assessment of internal control;
Require the Municipal Accountant and Municipal General Services Officer to strengthen the internal control procedures in (a) record-keeping; (b) report preparation; and, (c) reconciliation of reports with other offices, through establishment and documentation of these policies and procedures.

We recommended and Management agreed on the following:
Require the Municipal Accountant and Municipal Engineer the reconcile their records and determine the projects that are fully implemented, partially implemented and not yet implemented;
Request the Municipal Planning and Development Office to evaluate the contractual obligations of the Municipality on each project where the Municipality has outstanding payable and evaluate the corresponding sanctions that the clause in the contract/ memorandum of the agreement provides for failure to perform contractual obligations. Likewise, communicate to source agencies the reason for the non-performance of contractual obligations, if any;
Request the Municipal Accountant to coordinate to source agencies for the reversion of funds for completed projects;
Require the Municipal Engineering Office to submit a periodic report on the status of projects to the Municipal Planning and Development Office and to the Municipal Accounting Office for monitoring of the activities and for status of implementation.

We recommended and Management agreed on the following:
Establish a Composite Team in the Local Solid Waste Management Board (LSWMB) that will take charge of the development of policies pertaining to COVID-19 related health care wastes and for its implementation;
Require the Municipal Environment and Natural Resources Officer (MENDRO) and LSWMB to prepare a COVID-19 waste management plan and integrate the same into the 10- year Solid Waste Management Plan of the Municipality;
Direct the MENRO to conduct orientation and another information drive about the proper management of COVID-19 related wastes in barangays; and,
Require the MENRO and the Composite Team to devise activities to support the Barangay Ecological Solid Waste Management Committees in the proper handling of COVID-19 related health care wastes.
Direct the Municipal Environment and Natural Resources Officer and Municipal Health Officer to submit the microbial laboratory tests results of the treatment facility on COVID-19 related health care wastes to the DENR and/ or DOH for approval;
Require the Municipal Environment and Natural Resources Officer to conduct an orientation to waste disposal personnel on the classification of wastes being delivered for precautionary measures, maintaining a safe distance from, and avoiding direct contact with the wastes; and,
Facilitate in the establishment of systemic procedures in the recording and documentation of activities, particularly in the recording of COVID-19 related health care wastes that were collected, treated and disposed of.

We recommended that the LCE require the MT to 

(a) direct the COs to remit the collections to the LO at the end of the day to ensure their safety; 

(b) prepare the CRAAF in accordance with the rules and regulations for an accurate reporting of issued ORs; 

(c) regularly monitor the CTC forms issued to barangays; and 

(d) require the barangays concerned to turn-over the issued CTC that remained in their custody for a long period of time.

We recommended that the LCE require the 

(a) Municipal Engineer (ME) to 

(i) submit an explanation on the deficiencies noted; 

(ii) submit the lacking documentary requirements which include the revised construction schedule; revised PERT/CPM; Work Suspension Order (WSO) and Work Resumption Order (WRO) of noted PPAs; 

(iii) send written communication to the Contractors requiring them to provide notices requesting extension of contract time and citing therein the reasons for the delay in project completion; 

(iv) examine the facts and extent of the delay and recommend to the LCE the approval or disapproval of the Contract Time Extension; and

(v) if warranted, account for the negative slippage and impose liquidated damages to the Contractor; and

(b) MA to compute for the liquidated damages to be charged to the Contractor for failure to satisfactorily complete the work within the specified contract time.

We recommended that the LCE direct the ME, MA and members of the BAC to 

(a) submit the lacking documentary requirements which include (i) progress photos; and (ii) results of test analysis of construction materials; 

(b) comply with the guidelines on information and publicity on programs, projects and activities of government agencies; 

(c) complete the project activity logbook to indicate all required information such as the status of the on-going activity, new works started, construction equipment at the site each day and if operational or idle, the number of supervisory and non-supervisory personnel on site, and visitors to the site; 

(d) submit an explanation on the inconsistencies on the dimension/measurement of noted completed projects; and 

(e) cause the repair of the portion of the projects found defective at no additional cost to the Municipality.

